**Big-O notation is a method of representing the upper bound of an algorithm's running time. It gives the longest amount of time taken by the algorithm to complete.**

**Definition:** Let, f(n) and g(n) are two non-negative functions. And if there exists an integer n0 and constant C such that C > 0 and for all integers n > n0, f(n) ≤ c*g(n), then f(n) = Og(n).

**Example:** Consider the following algorithm: 

Algorithm Message(n) 
{ 
  for i=1 to n do 
    write(―Hello‖); 
}

**Time complexity:** The total frequency count is 2n+1. When computing the time complexity, we will neglect all the constants, hence ignoring 2 and 1 we will get n. Hence the time complexity becomes **O(n)**.

